<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-874-234  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 874 234.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Nov 13 1989 v11 n46 pS8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ignore the hype: SQL servers won't ease LAN traffic.andO;(cost-effectiveness of SQL database servers)(High-end focus)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crabb, Don.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Structured Query Language (SQL) servers, once found only onminicomputers and mainframes, are now widely available formicrocomputer local-area networks but entail many hidden costs.andO;The servers require high-end hardware: a fast 386 or 486 fileserver with 6 to 10Mbytes of RAM, OS/2, and a powerful networkoperating system.andP;  Hardware capable of running an SQL server isnearly as expensive as a small minicomputer.andP;  Translation softwaremay be needed to make the SQL server compatible with microcomputerworkstations; a customized applications programming interface isalso necessary for applications that do not already have SQLhooks.andP;  SQL servers have many advantages, but they do not reducenetwork traffic.andP;  System managers should exercise caution beforemaking a server purchase.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Structured Query LanguageData Base ServersCost Benefit AnalysisNetwork ManagementManagement of EDP.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>